ted on the southwestern tip of Sicily some ninety nautical miles northeast of the African shore. Ben-Yehoyada intertwines the town’s recent turbulent history—which has been fraught with conflicts over fishing rights, development projects, and how the Mediterranean should figure in Italian politics at large—with deep accounts of life aboard the Naumacho, linking ethnography with historical anthropology and political-economic analysis. Through this sophisticated approach, he crafts a new viewpoint on the historical processes of transnational region formation, one offered by these moving ships as they weave together new social and political constellations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFishers - Mediterranean Region. 0aFisherszMediterranean Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aItaly.  aMediterranean.  aSicily.  aTunisia.  ahistorical anthropology.  apolitical economy.  apolitical imaginary.  aregion formation.  ascale.  atransnationalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226451169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226451169/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles